text: RT @nextstrain: New #SARSCoV2 #COVID19 sequences from Brazil and Germany are up on nextstrain.  Both are exports from Italy and group toget…

The broadening of #COVID19 case definition by @CDCgov is an extremely welcome update. I believe this strikes the appropriate balance. Testing capacity has to follow however. And auxiliary sentinel surveillance for mild cases highly necessary. https://t.co/2Tu6oBOG8Y https://t.co/qgp4RdYy6v
RT @nextstrain: Five new #COVID19 genomes from viruses collected in late Jan / early Feb shared by @KoreaCDC shared to @AIDigest posted to…

This genome sits on a long branch without recent connections. However, this is similar to recent travel genomes collected during Feb. This pattern is occurring because only a small portion of #COVID19 cases are sequenced and so transmission chains are not fully sampled. 3/4 https://t.co/j3vK2cJbmJ

With the genome sequence from the community #COVID19 case from Solano County (https://t.co/tJveToSbY3), we have one half of the puzzle regarding escape from quarantine on Travis Air Force Base hypothesis. 1/4

This is a possibility that should be addressed. #COVID19 genome sequences from a couple quarantined individuals alongside the sequence of the community case would readily resolve this question. https://t.co/Df5IocJiWT

This is the worst thing I’ve ever been right about. @statnews reported on Jan 26 based on my conversation with @HelenBranswell my statement: “if it’s not contained shortly, I think we are looking at a pandemic”. https://t.co/37Fb9WZWDv 1/2

Containment has failed (though it did buy us time) and we are facing a pandemic. However, if countries can enact effective non-pharmaceutical interventions, it appears that spread can be substantially mitigated. 6/6

A few thoughts on where we stand on #COVID19. 
1. It appears there aren't massive undercounts of cases in China (https://t.co/MRXH6eu9Bb). This fits as with both my own phylodynamic analyses (https://t.co/fMUyNJdxJ6) and those of @erikmvolz (https://t.co/F0bbvNMdxg). 1/6

A difference of 10 years in genomic epidemiology:
- swine flu in 2009 had first reported cases 15 Feb and 11 partial sequences 77 days later (https://t.co/1SSgBVHwcN)
- #COVID2019 had first reported cases in early Dec and  119 full genomes 82 days later (https://t.co/JHWNUOwchc)

There are now localized #COVID19 outbreaks in Singapore, Hong Kong, Japan, Korea and Iran. I would have every reason to suspect other seeding events have taken hold elsewhere, but that many surveillance systems haven't yet caught on. 1/4

@JulianSapp #COVID19 was likely circulating in animals prior to Nov-2019. However, every indication is a recent animal-to-human spillover event(s) in Nov/Dec 2019 causing the human epidemic we are dealing with now.
